class Solution {
    public int minimumOperationsToMakeEqual(int x, int y) {
        int operations = 0;
        while (x != y) {
            if (x > y) {
                if (x % 11 == 0) {
                    x /= 11;
                } else if (x % 5 == 0) {
                    x /= 5;
                } else {
                    x--;
                }
            } else {
                if (y % 11 == 0) {
                    y /= 11;
                } else if (y % 5 == 0) {
                    y /= 5;
                } else {
                    y++;
                }
            }
            operations++;
        }
        return operations;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(abs(x-y))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iteratively adjusts either x or y closer to the other using the available operations. The loop continues until x and y are equal, and the number of operations performed is returned. The time complexity is directly proportional to the absolute difference between x and y, making it efficient for smaller input values. The space complexity is constant as no significant data structures are used. Energy implications are low due to the limited computational operations involved.

